id: pm-m1uz
title: "ADR: pm extensions are authored AND loaded as TypeScript via Node native type stripping"
description: "Policy ADR superseding the compiled-.js consequence of pm-2c28. With engines raised to Node >=22.18 (where Node strips TypeScript types on import by default), pm extensions/packages now ship their TypeScript source as the manifest `entry` (`./index.ts`) and the loader imports it directly — there is NO compiled `./index.js` artifact and NO build step. This is viable because the repo already mandates erasable TypeScript syntax (no enum/namespace/parameter-properties), which is exactly the subset Node native type stripping supports. Supersedes pm-2c28 alternative 'Load TypeScript directly at runtime (tsx/transpile-on-load)' whose rejection rationale ('adds a runtime transpile dependency') no longer applies to dependency-free native stripping."
type: Decision
status: closed
priority: 1
tags[6]: adr,"area:extensions","area:sdk",authoring,breaking-change,loader
created_at: "2026-06-24T07:23:40.616Z"
updated_at: "2026-06-24T08:01:22.815Z"
author: claude-code-agent
parent: pm-m2u1
resolution: "Accepted. Realized end-to-end by pm-2p7a with 100% coverage and green dogfood/gates: engines>=22.18, manifest entry ./index.ts across packages/examples/scaffolder, runtime-loaders resolve runtime.ts, CI/bundler on Node 22/24, docs reframed."
expected_result: "Extensions authored AND loaded as TypeScript (manifest entry ./index.ts, no compiled .js, no build step) with engines/CI/bundler/scaffolder/packages/docs aligned; tsc --noEmit as the author-time gate."
actual_result: Decision accepted and fully implemented (pm-2p7a); enforced by tsc --noEmit type-check gates and verified by 100% coverage + real ts-only dogfood.
dependencies[1]{id,kind,created_at,author,source_kind}:
  pm-2c28,related,"2026-06-24T07:24:32.188Z",null,null
close_reason: "Accepted and implemented by pm-2p7a. pm extensions/packages are now authored AND loaded as TypeScript via Node native type stripping (>=22.18): the .ts source is the manifest entry, no compiled .js, no build step. Supersedes the compiled-.js consequence of pm-2c28 (its 'authored fully in TypeScript' policy remains in force)."
body: "## Context\n\nADR [[pm-2c28]] established that pm extensions/SDK packages are authored fully in TypeScript, but kept the **compiled-`.js`** loading model: TS source (`index.ts`) was compiled to a committed `./index.js` that the manifest `entry` pointed at and the loader imported. That ADR explicitly *rejected* \"Load TypeScript directly at runtime (tsx/transpile-on-load)\" because it \"adds a runtime transpile dependency and startup cost.\"\n\nTwo things changed that calculus:\n\n1. **Node native type stripping is now stable and dependency-free.** Node >=22.18 (backport) / >=23.6 (default) strips TypeScript *types* on `import` with zero extra dependencies and negligible cost — it does not transpile, it erases type syntax. The previous rejection rationale (\"adds a runtime transpile dependency\") no longer applies.\n2. **The repo already mandates erasable TypeScript syntax** (no `enum`, `namespace`, parameter properties, `import =`) — which is *exactly* the subset Node native type stripping supports. The codebase was already writing the only TS dialect that strips cleanly.\n\nThe compiled-`.js` model carried real cost: a committed build artifact per package (drift risk between `.ts` and `.js`), a `build` step in every scaffold, and a split-brain where `index.ts` was the \"real\" source but `index.js` was what actually loaded.\n\n## Decision\n\nEvery pm extension and SDK package is authored **AND loaded** as TypeScript:\n\n1. The manifest `entry` points at the **`./index.ts` source itself** (not a compiled `./index.js`).\n2. The loader imports the `.ts` entry **directly** via Node's native type stripping. There is **no compiled `.js` artifact** committed or shipped, and **no build step**.\n3. Sibling modules are imported by their **real `.ts` extension** (`import { x } from \"./runtime.ts\"`) — `tsconfig` sets `allowImportingTsExtensions` (paired with `noEmit`). A `.js` specifier would not resolve under type stripping.\n4. Package `runtime.ts` modules import the SDK via the **published bare specifier `@unbrained/pm-cli/sdk`**, which self-resolves through the package's own `exports` map when the runtime-loader imports the runtime from inside the installed `@unbrained/pm-cli` tree (Node self-referencing).\n5. `engines.node` is raised to **`>=22.18.0`** (and `@types/node` to `^22`); CI, the nightly matrix, auto-release, the docs workflow, and the esbuild bundler target **Node 22/24** (Node 20 is dropped).\n6. Author-time type safety is preserved via `tsc --noEmit` (the `typecheck` gate); the scaffolder emits `typecheck`/`test` scripts (no `build`).\n\n## Rationale\n\n- Removes the committed-`.js` drift surface entirely — the source is the artifact.\n- Removes the build step from extension/package authoring: `pm extension/package init` → edit → install → run, with no compile in between.\n- Dependency-free: native type stripping ships in Node itself; no tsx/esbuild/ts-node at extension load time.\n- Aligns with the repo's existing erasable-syntax rule, so first-party packages stripped cleanly with no code changes beyond import specifiers.\n\n## Alternatives considered\n\n- **Keep the compiled-`.js` model (pm-2c28 status quo).** Rejected: perpetuates the `.ts`/`.js` split-brain, the per-package committed build artifact, and a build step in every scaffold, for no remaining benefit now that native stripping exists.\n- **Runtime transpile via tsx / on-load hook.** Rejected (as in pm-2c28) — adds a runtime dependency and cost. Native type stripping achieves direct `.ts` loading without either.\n\n## Consequences (breaking)\n\n- **Breaking for consumers:** the published `engines.node` becomes `>=22.18.0`; pm no longer runs on Node 20. Any host loading pm extensions needs Node >=22.18.\n- First-party `packages/pm-*` ship only `.ts` (committed `.js` removed); `gen-package-runtime-loaders.mjs` emits a single `.ts` loader per package (the JS loader variant is removed).\n- `docs/examples` reference extensions and the scaffolder output point `entry` at `./index.ts`; READMEs/docstrings reframed (no \"compiled to `.js`\").\n- The dogfood/smoke harnesses type-check the scaffold (`tsc --noEmit`) instead of building it, then install and invoke the `.ts` entry directly.\n\nImplemented by [[pm-2p7a]]. Supersedes the compiled-`.js` consequence of [[pm-2c28]] (which remains in force for \"authored fully in TypeScript\")."
